# MOC Operations

For **folder-based** projects (`Projects/<Name>/…`), a single **`MOC.md`** at the project root is the control plane—often **`Projects/<Name>/MOC.md`**, or **`Projects/<Name>-hub/MOC.md`** when `<Name>/` is reserved for a submodule clone root (see `.cursor/rules/moc-project-structure.mdc`). If the project uses a **flat hub** only (`Projects/<Name>.md` with no folder), treat that note as the hub instead (never both same slug).

## Required sections in MOC.md

- `## TL;DR`
- `## Outcome`
- `## Status`
- `## Quick Links` (project context index, technical `docs/README` when present, decisions, changelog, backlog, meetings, runbooks)
- `## Project folders (what goes where)`
- `## Open Decisions`
- `## Active Backlog`
- `## Recent Changes`
- `## Risks & Blockers`
- `## Next Actions`

## `## Project folders (what goes where)` (required body)

Each folder MOC must include this section with the table below (agents may paste verbatim). Keeps `docs/` vs `context/` distinct from decisions, backlog, and runbooks.

| Folder | Use for | Do not use for |
|--------|---------|----------------|
| **`context/`** | Client, commercial, onboarding, handover, short vault-side system summary; hub **`context/index.md`**. | Technical specs duplicated from the repo — link to **`docs/README`** instead. |
| **`docs/`** (when present) | Technical / product docs maintained with the codebase (architecture, data model, APIs, tests). Hub **`docs/README.md`**. | Client relationship notes, ADRs, backlog items — those live elsewhere. |
| **`decisions/`** | ADRs: “we chose A over B”, dated rationale. | Run steps or task lists. |
| **`runbooks/`** | Repeatable procedures when something breaks or needs an operator checklist. | Product requirements or ADR rationale. |
| **`backlog/`** | Prioritized work, bugs, features, owners. | Long-form reference docs. |
| **`meetings/`** | Notes tied to a specific meeting or call. | Evergreen architecture writeups. |
| **`changelog/`** | Dated “what changed” in the vault or project narrative. | Repo git history (unless you intentionally mirror a release note). |
| **`archive/`** | Superseded or parked project notes. | Active work. |

**One-line test:** if every open task and meeting disappeared, would this note still help someone understand the project? If yes, it probably belongs in **`context/`** or **`docs/`** (technical depth); if it is a choice record, **`decisions/`**; if it is “do this when”, **`runbooks/`**.

## Quick Links expectations

- Always link **`[[Projects/<Name>/context/index]]`** (or **`[[Projects/<Name>-hub/context/index]]`** when the hub lives in a `-hub` sibling folder) when the project uses a `context/` tree (create `context/index.md` if missing).
- When **`docs/`** exists under the hub, add **`[[Projects/<Name>/docs/README]]`** on its own line. When the technical repo is a submodule at **`Projects/<Name>/`** (clone root, no `docs/` subfolder), link **`[[Projects/<Name>/README]]`** (or the repo’s doc map path) from the **hub** MOC instead.

## Linking discipline

- Any new project note must be linked from `MOC.md` or from a child index linked by `MOC.md`.
- Use OFM wikilinks only: `[[Projects/<Project Name>/decisions/<note>]]`.
- Prefer one link per line under Quick Links for scannability.

## Style

- Bullets, not prose.
- Append-only for status, decisions, and changes history.
- Keep TL;DR to 1-3 sentences and regenerate on material status change.

## Agent behavior

- When editing a project note, update MOC.md cross-links and the `updated` frontmatter field.
- If a required section is missing in MOC.md, add it without reordering existing sections.
